WEBVTT

00:03.305 --> 00:12.493
OK.

00:03.305 --> 00:12.493
My name is Richard Brown, and I'm senior vice 
president of planning for the Woodlands

00:03.305 --> 00:12.493
Corporation. It's almost 1991, and I've spent the 
last 16 years here full time overseeing the real

00:13.814 --> 00:32.670
estate portfolio of Mitchell from the planning 
strategy and implementation phase, most of that

00:33.410 --> 00:37.576
time being spent on the new town called the 
Woodlands. I came here with a career that included

00:39.258 --> 01:00.067
25 years of running my own consulting 
professional firm of planners, engineers, and

00:39.258 --> 01:00.067
architects, which had, when I left, five offices, 
New York, New Jersey, Maryland, Atlanta,

00:39.258 --> 01:00.067
Georgia, Baton Rouge, Louisiana. And we 
specialized in a broad spectrum of professional

01:03.346 --> 01:11.017
services, but my real love was new community 
planning and development. I started my career in

01:11.578 --> 01:23.616
the early 50s as a professional engineer, 
broadening into urban planning and

01:11.578 --> 01:23.616
architecture, and became a consultant to many 
communities, both for their planning boards and

01:24.288 --> 01:34.583
governing bodies, as well as servicing the real 
estate development industry in a wide variety of

01:24.288 --> 01:34.583
projects from industrial development. How did 
you get into the new community concept or

01:34.603 --> 01:39.630
framework of things? I was retained by the Rouse 
Company to do the planning and engineering on a

01:39.650 --> 01:51.207
regional shopping mall in Willowbrook, New 
Jersey, called Willowbrook in Wayne, New Jersey.

01:51.743 --> 02:10.523
And in the process of that project, they announced 
to me that they had bought 11,000 acres in Maryland

01:51.743 --> 02:10.523
between Baltimore and Washington to do a new city, 
and wondered if I would come down and take a look at

01:51.743 --> 02:10.523
what they thought they wanted to do, since up to 
that point, they were regional moral developers.

02:11.083 --> 02:21.514
But Jim Rouse had an idea that suburban sprawl 
communities were not the best way to develop this

02:11.083 --> 02:21.514
nation. new communities were. And I went down 
there in 1965. Excuse me, how would you define a new

02:26.715 --> 02:32.664
community from that framework then or now, if 
there's any difference? Well, I think up until

02:32.744 --> 02:44.683
then and still prevailing today, the development 
industry are really geared up to be what I call

02:32.744 --> 02:44.683
shelter builders. They build houses, and your 
Sunday real estate section is full of houses. And

02:48.996 --> 02:51.919
they sell living rooms and ceiling fans and back 
decks. And the thrust really is the shelter

02:51.959 --> 02:56.966
they're selling. There's very few people who are 
community builders. A community builder not only

02:59.929 --> 03:13.827
provides a shelter, but he takes on the 
responsibility of providing a high quality of

02:59.929 --> 03:13.827
life for those residents to encompass all 
opportunities that are possible. to create an

03:14.093 --> 03:22.164
environment where people can live good lives and 
cover a broad cross-section of housing. Most

03:22.184 --> 03:27.011
subdivisions and developments are pretty 
monolithic in their price structure. New

03:27.672 --> 03:40.410
community attempts to have housing for the very 
poor, the very rich, and everybody in between in

03:27.672 --> 03:40.410
accordance with some economic demographic 
profile so that you have the vibrant mixture of

03:27.672 --> 03:40.410
people. And that's what new communities do. try to 
provide the retail and employment components of

03:44.215 --> 03:49.121
life also in the project. And that's part of the 
inception of the whole community plan? The

03:52.224 --> 03:59.553
conception of the plan is that you shouldn't have 
to spend one or two hours a day out of your life

03:52.224 --> 03:59.553
commuting to and from work. It would be great if you 
could get there in two to three minutes, which is

03:59.853 --> 04:05.239
the way I've lived for the last 30 years. Because 
I've lived in new towns since the early 60s. And I

04:10.685 --> 04:13.108
guess I've lost touch with what the real world is 
like. It's all right. That's all right. All right.

04:19.924 --> 04:26.958
So you were developing, you had become 
affiliated, I guess, with the new community town

04:19.924 --> 04:26.958
concept. Yeah, the Rouse Company asked me to come 
down, and after a few days of discussions, I was put

04:26.998 --> 04:34.472
in charge of, taking the conceptual plans and 
doing the hard line planning, the engineering,

04:36.258 --> 04:49.351
the county approvals that were necessary, take 
the bids, get the development built for the

04:36.258 --> 04:49.351
opening. So I was headed for that. That was a 
tremendous career. Yeah, it was a wonderful

04:52.655 --> 04:54.737
experience. How old were you then, roughly? I was 
in my, I guess, early 40s or late 30s.

05:05.992 --> 05:11.577
It was a wonderful experience to start with a clean 
slate and say, you know, where do the roads go?

05:11.617 --> 05:14.560
Where should the neighborhoods be? What is the 
fabric of community? What kind of an

05:16.782 --> 05:21.987
infrastructure should you have from the physical 
side as well as the social side? Can we take the

05:22.868 --> 05:32.657
experiences we've had and weave together a 
community that serves its people? I could mention

05:32.958 --> 05:41.087
that for a number of years I was mayor of a town in New 
Jersey undergoing very rapid growth. We're

05:41.327 --> 05:43.189
getting 3,000 building permits a year. And I knew 
all the problems of trying to provide libraries

05:43.830 --> 05:52.419
and recreation and public works expansions and 
services for a growing population. That was a

05:52.499 --> 05:54.301
great piece of experience. I think that was 
incredible. It really was. I bet very few

05:55.702 --> 05:57.745
architects have had that side. That's correct. So 
that was an in-depth. training session to help

06:02.506 --> 06:08.154
prepare me for new community development work, 
which is really what I love to do. And then how did

06:09.737 --> 06:12.140
the Texas Connection develop? After we got 
Columbia, Maryland open, the Routes Company had

06:13.522 --> 06:24.138
wanted me to stay on, but I had my own company, as I 
mentioned. I had taken a sabbatical for a year and a

06:24.218 --> 06:31.028
half to get Columbia open, so I said no. We expanded 
our activity in the new community field, and I

06:32.054 --> 06:41.068
think we did six or seven of the 12 or 13 HUD 
community projects. Flower Man was one. St.

06:42.650 --> 06:43.872
Charles was another.

06:47.298 --> 06:49.181
Ganonda was a third. We did Peachtree City, but at 
the last minute, they decided to stay private. And

06:55.691 --> 06:56.252
of course, we did that. That was in Georgia. That 
was in Atlanta. Yeah, southwest of Atlanta.

07:00.151 --> 07:02.114
That's still doing very nicely now. But the other 
HUD communities didn't make it, basically. No,

07:07.260 --> 07:10.144
they didn't make it for predetermined reasons. 
They had weak, inexperienced sponsors, not

07:10.184 --> 07:14.169
enough staying power financially. They were in 
poor locations where the markets were not strong.

07:18.355 --> 07:21.199
To build it in town, you need a great location. You 
need to be on Interstate Highway, which the

07:21.459 --> 07:24.383
Williams did. You need to be near a major airport, 
which it is. You need to be near an urban center

07:26.386 --> 07:29.770
that's expanding and has dynamic... vitality 
which houston does and so all the things will work

07:29.952 --> 07:58.052
you need a patient strong sponsor that can stand 
the deep investments that it takes the first 10

07:29.952 --> 07:58.052
years before you turn profitable a few people are 
committed to do that yeah they're all looking for a

07:29.952 --> 07:58.052
quick return every quarter yeah the bank wants you 
to borrow the money and return it that same year it

07:29.952 --> 07:58.052
takes a long time to develop these projects, it's 
nothing to think in terms of 20, 30, 40 years. But

08:04.023 --> 08:11.234
anyway, George Mitchell came to Columbia, 
Maryland, and visited me at my office there. I was

08:12.315 --> 08:13.697
pretty well known. I guess that was in 68, 69. and 
invited me down here to take a look at this

08:17.287 --> 08:19.510
property. I wonder who led him to you. Do you know, 
or other than just your reputation? No, I think it

08:23.614 --> 08:25.437
was the Columbia. Columbia had the reputation. It 
was the first new town on the East Coast, and when

08:26.778 --> 08:43.598
they came and found out that I had my role in it, and 
that I was a consulting firm with an office right

08:26.778 --> 08:43.598
there in the American City building in downtown 
Columbia, it was logical to continue. on and was a

08:44.287 --> 08:49.913
good source of potential clients and so forth. So 
George then retained my firm to come down and help.

08:54.177 --> 08:57.281
What did you think about his idea, that initial 
conversation? Do you remember any aspect of that?

09:00.865 --> 09:13.618
Yeah, I remember him asking me what it took to do a 
new town, and I told him it took a whole host of

09:00.865 --> 09:13.618
disciplines, engineers, planners, architects, 
economists, market people. and a commitment for

09:14.206 --> 09:19.051
long-term investment and so forth. And he said, 
OK. And I'm prepared to do all that. And so I became a

09:25.578 --> 09:29.082
consultant to the project. And just like with the 
Routes Company, when that was done, he said, well,

09:29.102 --> 09:34.248
why don't you stay on? And again, I said no and went 
away to do Peachtree City for Pipps Land Company,

09:35.169 --> 09:42.897
which I did for a year. including some work in 
Florida. But I kept getting phone calls. Why don't

09:46.998 --> 09:47.659
you come back? Why don't you come back? So when 
there was a break in major projects, I agreed to

09:48.520 --> 09:56.433
come back for a month and take a look. And at the end 
of that 30 days, I decided to stay. Oh, was that

09:58.616 --> 09:59.197
right? This was in the fall of 1974. But now, you had 
been here earlier than in 72? Well, I was here in 70,

10:07.432 --> 10:11.118
71, 72 when we did the planning. Then I went away for 
two years. Is this basic structure your

10:13.041 --> 10:19.310
conception, pretty much, the layout of the 
villages? Well, let me say, to be totally fair,

10:20.372 --> 10:27.182
there was a team of people involved. Robert 
Gladstone did the market studies economic

10:30.650 --> 10:37.044
reports which have a strong bearing on what you 
build because there's a market there to buy it. We

10:38.346 --> 10:44.760
had McCard here from the University of 
Pennsylvania who was an environmentalist who

10:38.346 --> 10:44.760
hammered home the preservation of the forest 
concept and the forest preserves, which really is

10:45.230 --> 10:49.595
our signature. And we still respect a lot of what he 
said, some of which we had to change.

10:57.504 --> 11:02.769
Nevertheless,

10:57.504 --> 11:02.769
he had a very positive influence. And then William 
Pereira, an architect on the West Coast. George

11:06.113 --> 11:09.317
used to say, well, we've got the best from the West 
Coast and the best from the East Coast. And Richard

11:10.098 --> 11:12.300
Brown, associate, and he William Carrera got 
together, and we had numerous workshops over the

11:12.550 --> 11:22.829
year doing concept planning, master planning. 
And we tried a lot of things. We tried linear plans.

11:25.434 --> 11:28.119
We tried historic gridiron patterns. And in the 
end, I think the Columbia model proved to be the

11:32.277 --> 11:39.346
most viable, which was a series of residential 
villages and a very strong employment corridor

11:32.277 --> 11:39.346
along I-45. Your initial plan, what was the 
acreage? Was it 7,000? 17,000. 17,000, yeah. It's

11:45.273 --> 11:46.674
25 now. But it was 17 at that time. When I came back 
full time, one of the first things I did was lobby,

11:49.117 --> 11:58.208
pick up that next 8,000 acres all the way out to 
2978, which was a major acquisition. But George

11:58.809 --> 12:00.411
became convinced. If we didn't do that, by the way, 
we'd be nearing the end of this project by now.

12:06.646 --> 12:11.933
Because we needed that to grow.

12:11.953 --> 12:15.137
So you come back here then in 74.

12:16.619 --> 12:19.783
And that was kind of a tenuous time. Yeah, oil 
shortages were coming on and the economy was flat

12:20.765 --> 12:30.077
and it was tough getting going. By energy going up, 
they could afford to bridge the gap of deficit

12:30.378 --> 12:38.648
years until the project would turn profitable. 
What intrigued you about coming here, say,

12:38.788 --> 12:43.134
instead of going to another project somewhere 
else? Well, I think it was, frankly, the biggest

12:43.735 --> 12:47.259
project. I really believed that it had all the 
components for success, as I mentioned, on a state

12:48.941 --> 12:57.111
highway near a growing metropolitan area. the 
largest in the country at that time, near a major

12:57.952 --> 13:02.937
airport. So those compounds were there. George's 
personal commitment to me that this was not a get in

13:04.759 --> 13:11.346
and get out kind of a project. He was going to see it 
through. They were going to fund it. And the thing

13:14.309 --> 13:26.541
that appealed to me most of all the sponsors of New 
Towns, most of them were either in the real estate

13:14.309 --> 13:26.541
business or some other affiliated business, but 
nobody had such a strong main business. I think

13:29.171 --> 13:37.340
Mitchell's energy division, and we used to say, 
you know, Mitchell is 80% energy and 20% real

13:29.171 --> 13:37.340
estate. So real estate's very cyclonic. If you're 
going into a project that's going to take 30 years,

13:40.823 --> 13:46.890
there's going to be good times, there's going to be 
bad times, there's going to be good times, there's

13:40.823 --> 13:46.890
going to be bad times. It's going to go up and down 
two or three times a decade. And if that's all you

13:49.753 --> 13:53.997
do, when you hit those troughs, you're in a lot of 
trouble. I saw the energy division as the means to

13:54.567 --> 14:02.478
bridge those gaps, where when things are good, we 
break it all in. When things get bad, we've got the

14:02.838 --> 14:05.963
staying power. I never would have sold my company, 
you know, just to come out of purely real estate

14:06.543 --> 14:11.771
companies. I know they're so flaky. They don't 
have the staying power when you hit a recession.

14:18.079 --> 14:21.604
But since it was a minor part of the company's 
business, you know, I figured that gave it a

14:22.124 --> 14:27.612
stability that most real estate companies don't 
have. It's a very important thing. And people will

14:30.136 --> 14:34.442
admit, if you look back, that if it weren't for 
energy, we wouldn't have produced some of the gas.

14:35.844 --> 14:43.696
And then, of course, we had the double whammy in the 
mid-'80s, when both energy and real estate went

14:35.844 --> 14:43.696
down, and we had some tough sledding. But now, both 
of them up again. I think it's going to work out all

14:46.921 --> 14:48.363
right. I think that... Do you think, 
incidentally, that... Right now, it's

14:51.757 --> 14:59.025
comparable in any way, say, to the mid-'70s when 
things began to recycle again. You know, the

14:59.045 --> 15:02.189
energy oil went up and building... I like to think 
that we've learned something from that and we

15:02.209 --> 15:07.015
aren't going to go... I think they'll find a 
solution in the next 6 to 12 months in the Middle

15:07.175 --> 15:13.482
East. It'll be a compromise that will moderate 
things back to, I think, where it will stay...

15:18.757 --> 15:28.346
between $20 and $30 a barrel, and maybe $25, where I 
think it's a healthy thing for the energy

15:18.757 --> 15:28.346
companies, but not a depressant on the rest of the 
world economy. And I think that's very important.

15:31.669 --> 15:32.831
But I think that will happen. And instead of having 
the kind of crazy boom they had in the late 70s that

15:32.851 --> 15:44.502
only could foresee a collapse that happened, 
hopefully that won't happen again. Now, when NAD

15:48.524 --> 15:50.427
See, I may be jumping your head too far. But in 82, 
that's about the time you begin to hit the slide

15:51.849 --> 15:56.315
again in the Woodlands. What are you doing now? I 
mean, can you sort of reconstruct that particular

15:58.218 --> 16:01.422
period? You've been in the Boone, and now what 
happens is basically through the 80s. Well, we

16:06.309 --> 16:07.911
reduced staff. Our planning department used to be 
18. It went back to six. It was a time to tighten

16:11.837 --> 16:17.485
belts and to try to... survive what everybody 
said, what you know. Because we know,

16:23.337 --> 16:25.600
historically, it's cyclonic. When things are 
bad, they don't stay bad. They will change.

16:28.343 --> 16:30.004
They'll either get worse or they'll get better. 
And we knew it would get better. And sure enough, it

16:32.507 --> 16:35.170
did. And the thing that happened, which was very 
surprising but very enlightening, as the real

16:35.190 --> 16:47.303
estate market shrunk as far as demand goes in 
Houston, so did The development industries

16:47.992 --> 16:50.435
shrink. And the subdivision developers, the 
shelter builders, as I said, the people who didn't

16:50.455 --> 16:59.286
build communities, their projects died 
illegally. And what happened where the

16:59.666 --> 17:17.408
Newtown-type projects, which the Woodlands fits 
the Newtown definition the best, but there are

16:59.666 --> 17:17.408
others that are similar but not quite as complete, 
like the King Woods and the First Colonies and the

16:59.666 --> 17:17.408
Copperfields, those planned communities, which 
fortunately ring Clear Lake City, ring Houston,

17:18.164 --> 17:39.184
and that's an important point to mention later, 
those communities which had been getting between

17:18.164 --> 17:39.184
5 and 7 percent of the market share during the good 
times wound up getting 50 to 55 percent of the

17:18.164 --> 17:39.184
market share. So while the pie got smaller, the new 
community project share of that pie got bigger and

17:39.624 --> 17:45.209
bigger. So we didn't suffer the total collapse 
that the individual subdivision developers saw.

17:52.643 --> 18:00.692
And that was largely because of the builders or 
whatever lost their financing, was it, do you

17:52.643 --> 18:00.692
think? That's probably part of it, but also I think 
that the marketplace began to understand and

18:01.933 --> 18:12.285
perceive that a new community environment Was it 
better protection for their real estate

18:12.907 --> 18:19.094
investment than somebody's bedroom in the 
subdivision? Right, somebody's gridiron

18:19.815 --> 18:35.674
bedroom community project that didn't have the 
recreation, social, cultural, entertainment,

18:19.815 --> 18:35.674
and employment opportunities where the quality 
of life wasn't assured because of the

18:19.815 --> 18:35.674
completeness of the program and the plan. And then 
that was traditional Texas, Houston

18:35.694 --> 18:41.260
construction style until the advent of 
equipment. across the whole country. And I'm not

18:43.029 --> 18:56.082
trying to compare anything unfavorably, but 
Friendswood, I guess, would have been the largest

18:43.029 --> 18:56.082
developer in the south part of town in that style. 
Clear Lake City. Clear Lake City, right. Are they

18:58.344 --> 19:01.847
moving more into your style of development now, 
you think? No, I don't think so. I think everyone

19:04.870 --> 19:11.196
has their own program.

19:11.851 --> 19:20.486
Our biggest competitor, because the two of us are 
the north side of town, their villages are

19:11.851 --> 19:20.486
economically very monolithic. This village, if 
you want a price range house, $150,000 to

19:22.089 --> 19:26.978
$200,000, you live in that village. If you want an 
$80,000 house, you live in another village. Where

19:30.624 --> 19:36.795
the woodlands, we have the dynamics of a complete 
socioeconomic mixed formula for the whole

19:30.624 --> 19:36.795
village. And we get more vitality and reality to 
